      },
      {
        "id" : "a8f8a2fb-90b4-4b60-bba2-972d306fe71a",
        "parentId" : "c5d961bd-9b38-4071-be75-6577978c72fb",
        "authorId" : "1eec7f68-de25-4f88-827c-00769c75a2d7",
        "body" : "When we see `file://` we consider it part of the root path, so it isn't matched. You can see examples of root paths in the comments for `getRootLength`.\r\n\r\nThis was for cases like `C:\\dir\\\\file` or `file:///dir//file`, though I've done some testing recently that both Windows, POSIX, and web URLs all treat `//` as a \"valid\" path, though you can't actually create it.",
        "createdAt" : "2021-05-19T19:15:07Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2021-05-19T19:15:08Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "1eec7f68-de25-4f88-827c-00769c75a2d7",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "c4e08bd7-9e4d-4170-895a-bb18c8941f58",
        "parentId" : "c5d961bd-9b38-4071-be75-6577978c72fb",
        "authorId" : "4fe07f9f-2018-4a29-969c-e58ed20233c7",
        "body" : "What Ron said - it's for `//`, except in the root.  (That \"except in the root\" is why we can't use a regex to make the replacement.)",
        "createdAt" : "2021-05-19T19:45:51Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2021-05-19T19:45:51Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "4fe07f9f-2018-4a29-969c-e58ed20233c7",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      }
